column1: Cyber NextGen Firewall Selection
column31: There is currently a hold on selecting the Cyber vendor due to financial and budget discussions. The private cloud design is dependent on the Cyber vendor. The Private Cloud Security block design has an exteral dependency on the final decision of the NextGen firewall selection
column142: Selecting one of the three vendors that supports NextGen firewall vendors    Fortinet, Check Point and Palo Alto which are design has been based on
column237: 24/Aug/21 8:42 AM;jamie.harris2@rtx.com;8/24 - Pending date for escalation; vendor selection put on pause for financial discussions. Identifying date needed for selection;;;
column238: 24/Aug/21 3:07 PM;damalia.thomas@rtx.com;Cyber team has no current eta on when NextGen firewall will be selected. The Private Cloud LLD must be updated to reflect the design of the selected vendor and takes an est of 60 days to complete. Workload migrations cannot tak place without the firewall in PDC1 and Ashburn colo's;;;
column239:
25/Aug/21 10:14 AM;Ben.Taylor@rtx.com;8/22.  [Ben Taylor comments]  Troy Abraham has the NGFW RFP ready but the budget has not been appropriated.  Requested a date for the decision to release the RFP and the date for Vendor selection.  No dates are known at this time.

RISK:  If the Next Gen Firewall (NGFW) vendor is not selected by September 15, the PDC1 and Ashburn Colos will not be properly equipped for operation or according to design by Q1 2022.;;;
column240: 26/Aug/21 10:15 AM;Ben.Taylor@rtx.com;NOPT-3732 and NOPT-725 also address the NGFW funding and risk issue.;;;

column244: 22/Sep/21 10:01 AM;damalia.thomas@rtx.com;Cyber team is working on competitive bids between two vendors and expected to order firewall hardware for East, Greenfield and West Colo. There is a total of 6 to be ordered. ;;;

************************************************************************************************
From: Didier Weizman 
Sent: Friday, September 3, 2021 12:33 PM
To: Dan Doyle <DoyleD_corp_g@rtxusers.mail.onmicrosoft.us>; Pavia, Mauro Export License Required - US RTX <mauro.pavia@rtx.com>
Cc: Joel Helgerson <jch@raytheon.com>; Marty Tice <mtic@raytheon.com>; Evan Marks <evan.marks@rtx.com>; Hill, Richard P Export License Required - US RTX <richard.p.hill@rtx.com>; Stevens, Gregory A RTX <gregory.stevens@rtx.com>; Robb Wilber <robb.wilber@rtx.com>
Subject: International Performance Hubs quote request

Dan, Mauro,

Attached is the BOM for the International Performance Hubs (PH). It includes both Cisco and Non-Cisco components for the PHs in Singapore, London, Frankfurt, Australia, and MENA. Can you please start the quoting process? All subscriptions and warranties need to be priced as 12 month terms. It’s to be noted that we will be refining the BOM in the next few weeks:
•	Firewalls are yet to be identified for pricing                         
•	Services and Identity Servers are still in technical refinement                                                     
•	Cabling and transceivers need refinement                                           
•	Power cords need further refinement according to local Equinix requirements                                                   
•	Load-balancers need to be finalized and included                                                            
•	Equipment at current hubs are being reviewed for EOL status                                                   
                                             
Let me know if you have any questions or concerns.

Thank you!

Regards,
Didier


Didier Weizman
IT Fellow
Global Infrastructure Services
Raytheon Technology
880 Technology Park Drive
Billerica, MA 01821

Cell: (781) 727-0260

column1: ADX Migrations: Enterprise Applications - Dependency - Application Data for Remediations
column31:
Four key attributes for the program: (1) Application Name, (2) Application Owner/Lead, (3) Application Administrator and (4) Active Directory Dependency.

 

Program requires ownership in the Application Identification and Remediation space.

 

Currently 6,354 known applications - require confirmed app owner, admin and AD dependency for next steps.  One AD dependency is identified, required remediation to support ADX domain, testing and validation.

 

Acceptance criteria - 100% identified applications with AD dependency with full remediation

*From:* Mac MCDANIEL <[mac.mcdaniel@raytheon.com|mailto:mac.mcdaniel@raytheon.com]> 
 *Sent:* Thursday, July 29, 2021 5:04 PM
 *To:* Naveed Mahmood <[naveed.mahmood@raytheon.com|mailto:naveed.mahmood@raytheon.com]>
 *Cc:* PATRICK DUNN <[patrick_dunn@raytheon.com|mailto:patrick_dunn@raytheon.com]>; TAVIS GILLARD <[tavis.gillard@raytheon.com|mailto:tavis.gillard@raytheon.com]>
 *Subject:* RE: Request for Guidance/Assistance: Vulnerability scanning for Linux systems in the Cloud (SAP ID 6621609 - RTX LDAP)

 

Hi Naveed,

 

For Linux systems in the Cloud, you can add SSH_svc-scanCorp_DevCloud account to the sudoers group OR if you want to provide the Linux local admin account that would also work.

 

Select the “Cloud” option and then Check the box if systems are on the domain. Add *SSH_svc-scanCorp_DevCloud* account to the sudoers group or if using Centrify, *us\svc-scanCorp* to the backup operators group)

 

If you prefer to provide local admin creds, then add them as seen below (admin123 is just an example).

 

 

 

 

If you’d like to connect via zoom, you can share your screen and we’ll get this submitted. No problem.

 

 

Thank you,

Mac

column1: NET-013-Firewall Design & Implementation
column31:
Document the firewall rules for each service. Review & approve the documents for each service.

Services will be deployed in waves between performance hub readiness and the end of Q1 2022.

List of services: 
 ADX, Heritage AD, LDAP, VDS, PKI, SSO, PAM, Reverse Proxy, Cisco ISE, EIM, Patch Management, Monitoring, Bastion host, VMware

LOE: 50% Design / 50% implementation

column1: NET - 009 - EPIC - NOC/SOC Packet Tapping and Data Storage RACI
column31:
*The intent of this Network Operations Data Strategy / Platform Integration Epic is to:*
 # *Identify Network Operations Tools across Cyber and Infrastructure that use the same network data sources (e.g. Network Configurations, Flows, Packets) for use in analysis with Infra Ops or Cyber Sec Ops applications.*
 # *Create a Network Tools RACI owners for Network Packet Capture, both in-line, hot and cold storage for analysis*:
 ##  Data source capture and live storage (e.g. Network Taps, Packet Broker, NetScout Infinistream; PCAP Indexing/Storage) (2-weeks - 1 month).
 ##  Data conversion and/or enrichment required for Network Tools to work with this source data (e.g. Packet Encryption/Decryption, PCAP Flow Metadata tagging).
 ##  Data transformation (ETL/ELT) and API integrations required between tooling platforms and historical full-resolution flows / packet data (<60-90 days historical data).
 # *Identify what data needs to be forwarded to and ingested within the Splunk SIEM*:
 ##  From a Network Tools perspective (audit logs, syslog, event logs, application logs) and the process to initiate.
 ##  Indexing locations for use in Cyber Sec Ops or EIS Infra Ops.
 ##  Maintaining stored network data and who should have access.

 

*Network Operations Tooling Platforms that use captured and forwarded packet / flow data for analysis:*
 * *Network Performance Monitoring (NPM)*: NetScout nGeniusONE
 ** Full Resolution Packet Capture / In-Line Packet Analysis via Infinistreams
 ** (<30 Day) Deep-Packet Analysis for Network Troubleshooting
 ** Session Analysis for use in Application Troubleshooting
 ** In-line packet decryption for use in Application Troubleshooting
 * *Full-Resolution Packet Capture and Storage (PCAP)*: Fidelis PCAP
 ** Full Resolution Packet Capture & Data Storage
 ** Flow Metadata Tagging and In-Database Analysis
 ** Packet Analysis using stored packet and flow data past 60 days
 ** Intrusion Detection and threat database
 * *Intrusion Detection System (IDS):* Arkime IDS

*Network Operations Configuration Tools that scan for and store vendor device configurations, have CLI access to devices through an interface, and leverages RADIUS/TACACS:*
 * *OpenGear Lighthouse & Opengears:* Out of Band Management
 * *VMWare Smart Assurance (Voyence/EMC Smarts):* Heterogeneous Network Configuration Management (Routing, Switching, FW/Proxy, Load Balancer)
 * *Cisco Prime Infrastructure:* Cisco Network WAN/LAN Configuration Management
 * _*Cisco DNA Center:* Next Generation Cisco Prime_
 * *Cisco Firepower Management Center:* Cisco Network Security Configuration & Event Management
